{"id":"fad6727b-c7b3-401c-859c-cf1f9e4eb017","timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:12:18.567Z","type":"gemini","content":"No, the **Antigravity CLI was not downloaded** during the Nix rebuild. \n\nI had to remove the Antigravity code from your configuration because the GitHub URL I tried (Option A) doesn't exist (since the tool is currently proprietary/closed-source). On NixOS, if a package isn't in the official `nixpkgs` or a working flake, it won't be downloaded automatically.\n\n### Why Jan Froze Your System\nYou are running an **NVIDIA RTX 4050 Laptop GPU** with **6GB of VRAM**. \n*   **Llama 3.1 8B (Q4):** Uses ~4.9GB. This is safe.\n*   **Gemma 4 / Qwen 3.5 9B:** These models, once you add the \"Context Window\" (memory for the conversation history) and the overhead of your Linux desktop (Hyprland), will easily exceed 6GB.\n\nWhen VRAM is full, the system tries to \"swap\" the model into your regular System RAM. Because the GPU and CPU have to fight over the memory bus, this usually causes a **hard system freeze** on Linux.\n\n---\n\n### How to get Antigravity CLI now\nSince we can't use the Nix flake method yet, follow these steps to install it manually:\n\n1.  **Download:** Go to [antigravity.google](https://antigravity.google) in your browser and download the **Linux x86_64** binary.\n2.  **Move to your bin:**\n    ```bash\n    mkdir -p ~/.local/bin\n    mv ~/Downloads/agy ~/.local/bin/agy\n    chmod +x ~/.local/bin/agy\n    ```\n3.  **Run Migration:**\n    ```bash\n    agy plugin import gemini\n    ```\n\n### How to prevent the Jan Freezes\nTo avoid another hard freeze when testing models:\n1.  **Check VRAM usage first:** Keep a terminal open with `nvtop` or `nvidia-smi -l 1`.\n2.  **Limit Layers:** In Jan AI, go to the model settings and look for \"GPU Layers\" (or \"N-GPU-Layers\"). Instead of \"Auto,\" set it to a specific number (e.g., 20 or 25) to ensure some of the model stays on your CPU, leaving breathing room for your VRAM.\n3.  **Use Llama 3.1 8B:** It is currently the \"sweet spot\" for 6GB cards.\n\n**Since your Hyprland errors are gone and your system is stable again, would you like me to help you create a custom Nix derivation for the `agy` binary so it *does* get managed by your system configuration?** (This is the proper \"Nix way\" to handle proprietary binaries).","thoughts":[{"subject":"Investigating Jan's Freeze","description":"I'm currently diagnosing why Jan froze again. My hypothesis centers on VRAM over-allocation during a large model load. I'm also verifying if the `antigravity` binary was included in the recent Nix rebuild.","timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:12:12.292Z"},{"subject":"Confirming Antigravity's Absence","description":"I've confirmed `antigravity` wasn't installed; my prior attempt to add it failed due to an invalid URL, so I reverted the changes. The system rebuilds cleanly without it. I'm now focused on explaining Jan's VRAM freeze and will provide manual installation steps and VRAM management tips.","timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:12:14.115Z"},{"subject":"Investigating VRAM Limits","description":"I'm now considering how much VRAM specific models consume and how that might cause Jan's freeze. I'll also look into setting VRAM limits within Ollama to prevent future system hangs.","timestamp":"2026-05-21T03:12:14.892Z"}],"tokens":{"input":76178,"output":620,"cached":0,"thoughts":851,"tool":0,"total":77649},"model":"gemini-3-flash-preview"}
